SIMPLE: trip
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trip
<hw>Trip</hw> <pr>(tr⟦icr⟧p)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Tripped</conjf> <pr>(tr⟦icr⟧pt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Tripping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>trippen</ets>; akin to D. <ets>trippen</ets>, Dan.
<ets>trippe</ets>, and E. <ets>tramp</ets>. See
<er>Tramp</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To move with light, quick steps; to walk or move
lightly; to skip; to move the feet nimbly; -- sometimes followed by
<xex>it</xex>. See <er>It</er>, 5.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This horse anon began to <qex>trip</qex> and dance.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Come, and <qex>trip</qex> it, as you go,⟦br⟧
On the light fantastic toe.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She bounded by, and <qex>tripped</qex> so light⟦br⟧
They had not time to take a steady sight.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make a brief journey or pleasure excursion;
<as>as, to <ex>trip</ex> to Europe</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To take a quick step, as when in danger of losing
one's balance; hence, to make a false step; to catch the foot; to lose
footing; to stumble.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Fig.: To be guilty of a misstep; to commit an
offense against morality, propriety, or rule; to err; to mistake; to
fail.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Till his tongue <xex>trip</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A blind will thereupon comes to be led by a blind understanding;
there is no remedy, but it must <qex>trip</qex> and stumble.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Virgil is so exact in every word that none can be changed but for
a worse; he pretends sometimes to <qex>trip</qex>, but it is to make you
think him in danger when most secure.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What? dost thou verily <qex>trip</qex> upon a word?</q>
<rj><qau>R. Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trip
<hw>Trip</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to stumble, or
take a false step; to cause to lose the footing, by striking the feet
from under; to cause to fall; to throw off the balance; to supplant; --
often followed by <xex>up</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>trip</ex> up a man in
wrestling</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The words of Hobbes's defense <qex>trip</qex> up the heels of his
cause.</q> <rj><qau>Abp. Bramhall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <mark>(Fig.)</mark>: <def>To overthrow by depriving of
support; to put an obstacle in the way of; to obstruct; to cause to
fail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>trip</qex> the course of law, and blunt the sword.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To detect in a misstep; to catch; to convict; also
called <altname>trip up</altname>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These her women can <qex>trip</qex> me if I err.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To raise (an anchor)
from the bottom, by its cable or buoy rope, so that it hangs free.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>To pull (a yard) into a perpendicular position for
lowering it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>To release, let fall, or set
free, as a weight or compressed spring, as by removing a latch or
detent; to activate by moving a release mechanism, often
unintentionally; <as>as, to <ex>trip</ex> an alarm</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Trip
<hw>Trip</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A quick, light step; a
lively movement of the feet; a skip.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His heart bounded as he sometimes could hear the <qex>trip</qex>
of a light female step glide to or from the door.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A brief or rapid journey; an excursion or
jaunt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I took a <qex>trip</qex> to London on the death of the queen.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A false step; a stumble; a misstep; a loss of
footing or balance. Fig.: An error; a failure; a mistake.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Imperfect words, with childish <qex>trips</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Each seeming <qex>trip</qex>, and each digressive start.</q>
<rj><qau>Harte.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A small piece; a morsel; a bit.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>trip</xex> of cheese.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A stroke, or catch, by which a wrestler causes his
antagonist to lose footing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And watches with a <qex>trip</qex> his foe to foil.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>It is the sudden trip</qex> in wrestling that fetches a man
to the ground.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A single board, or tack, in
plying, or beating, to windward.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A herd or flock, as of sheep, goats, etc.</def>
<mark>[Prov. Eng. & Scott.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A troop of men; a host.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Robert of Brunne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A flock of widgeons.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tripalmitate</ent>⟦br⟧
